# Core Rules

## Design Principle: Rust-First

All logic lives in Rust. SDKs (C#, Python) are thin wrappers that marshal data and call FFI functions. Never implement game logic in an SDK.

## Layer Architecture

Dependencies flow DOWN only. No upward or same-layer imports.

- Layer 1 (Core): `libs/` — graphics, platform, ecs, logger
- Layer 2 (Engine): `goud_engine/src/` — core, assets, sdk
- Layer 3 (FFI): `goud_engine/src/ffi/`
- Layer 4 (SDKs): `sdks/` — GoudEngine (C#), python
- Layer 5 (Apps): `examples/`

## Build and Test Commands

```bash
cargo build                        # Debug build
cargo build --release              # Release build
cargo test                         # Run all tests
cargo test -- --nocapture          # Show test output
cargo check                        # Fast type-check
cargo fmt --all -- --check         # Format check
cargo clippy -- -D warnings        # Lint check
./dev.sh --game <name>             # Run an example game
./dev.sh --sdk python --game <name> # Run a Python example
```

## Version Management

ALWAYS increment version before packaging:

```bash
./increment_version.sh             # Patch (0.0.X)
./increment_version.sh --minor     # Minor (0.X.0)
./increment_version.sh --major     # Major (X.0.0)
```

## Local Development Cycle

```bash
./increment_version.sh    # 1. Bump version
./build.sh                # 2. Build everything
./package.sh --local      # 3. Deploy to local NuGet
./dev.sh --game <g> --local # 4. Test with example
```

## Commit Conventions

- Use conventional commit messages (feat:, fix:, refactor:, docs:, test:, chore:)
- Never use `--no-verify` on commits
- Never force-push to main/master
- Pre-commit hook runs: format, clippy, basic tests, Python SDK
- Pre-push hook runs: full test suite, doctests, security audit (`cargo deny check`)

## Anti-Patterns

- Implementing logic in SDKs instead of Rust core
- Skipping version increment before packaging
- Files exceeding 500 lines
- Using `todo!()` or `unimplemented!()` in production code
- Tests without assertions or with `#[ignore]`
- `#[allow(unused)]` without justification
- Using `unwrap()`/`expect()` in library code — use `Result` instead
